"Rull V., Vegas-Vilarrúbia T.","Unexpected biodiversity loss under global warming in the neotropical Guayana Highlands: A preliminary appraisal",2006,"Global Change Biology","12","1",,"1","9",,,10.1111/j.1365-2486.2005.001080.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33645847234&partnerID=40&md5=f351781ce05cba215a43f65d6a2504d2","Departament de Biologia Animal, Biologia Vegetal i Ecologia, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, 08193 Bellaterra, Barcelona, Spain; Departament d'Ecologia, Universitat de Barcelona, Av Diagonal 645, 08028 Barcelona, Spain","Rull, V., Departament de Biologia Animal, Biologia Vegetal i Ecologia, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, 08193 Bellaterra, Barcelona, Spain; Vegas-Vilarrúbia, T., Departament d'Ecologia, Universitat de Barcelona, Av Diagonal 645, 08028 Barcelona, Spain","The fully vegetated summits of the table mountains that form the Guayana Highlands (GH), in northern South America, hold amazing biodiversity and endemism levels, and unique vegetation types. In spite of their present-day healthy appearance, their biota is seriously threatened of habitat loss by upward displacement, because of the projected warming for the end of this century. Available data are still insufficient for a definite assessment, but preliminary estimations based on representative endemic vascular plant species show that roughly one-tenth to one-third of them would loss their habitat with the 2-4°C temperature increase predicted for the region by AD 2100. Given the underlying endemism, the eventual loss of biodiversity will be of global nature. Other mountain ranges around the world with similar characteristics of the GH, namely topographical isolation, high endemism and absence of nival stage because of the lower altitude, would be under similar unexpected risk, and should be urgently considered for conservation purposes. © 2005 Blackwell Publishing Ltd.","Biodiversity; Conservation; Endemism; Extinction; Global warming; Guayana; Habitat loss; High mountains; Migration; Tropics","biodiversity; biota; ecological impact; endemism; extinction; global warming; habitat loss; vegetation type; Guiana Highlands; South America; Tracheophyta",,,,,,"Berry, P.E., Holst, B.K., Yatskievych, K., (1995) Flora of the Venezuelan Guayana, 1. , Introduction Missouri Botanical Garden Press, St Louis; Briceño, H.O., Schubert, C., Geomorphology of the Gran Sabana, Guayana Shield, Southeastern Venezuela (1990) Geomorpholohy, 3, pp. 125-141; Bush, M.B., Distributional change and conservation on the Andean flank, a palaeoecological perspective (2002) Global Ecology and Biogeography, 11, pp. 463-473; Chapin, F.S., Callaghan, T.V., Bergeron, Y., Global change and the boreal forest: Thresholds, shifting states or gradual change? (2004) Ambio, 33, pp. 361-365; Clubbe, C., Threats to biodiversity (1996) Global Environmental Issues, , (eds Blackmore R, Reddish A), Hodder & Stoughton, London; Dirnböck, T., Dullinger, S., Grabherr, G., A regional impact assessment of climate and land-use change on apline vegetation (2003) Journal of Biogeography, 30, pp. 401-417; Dullinger, S., Dirnböck, T., Grabher, G., Patterns of shrub invasion into high mountain grasslands of the northern calcareous Alps, Austria (2003) Arctic, Antarctic and Alpine Research, 35, pp. 434-441; Farrera, I., Harrison, S.P., Prentice, I.C., Tropical climates at the last glacial maximum: A new synthesis of terrestrial paleoclimate data. I. Vegetation, lake-levels and geochemistry (1999) Climate Dynamics, 15, pp. 823-856; Givnish, T.J., Evans, T.M., Zjhra, M.L., Molecular evolution, adaptative radiation, and geographic diversification in the amphiatlantic family Rapateaceae: Evidence from ndhF sequences and morphology (2000) Evolution, 54, pp. 1915-1937; Grabherr, G., Gottfried, M., Pauli, H., Climate effects on mountain plants (1994) Nature, 369, p. 448; Halloy, S.R.P., Mark, A.F., Climate-change effects on alpine plant biodiversity: A New Zealand perspective on quantifying t